          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":60,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"sunday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"24–26 km at easy pace (5:07–5:39/km). Keep it conversational — if you can't hold a sentence, slow down. This is your aerobic foundation, not a race simulation.\"},\"monday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest or gentle walking. Your body does its best adaptation work when you're not running. Think of today as part of the training, not a gap in it.\"},\"tuesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"12–14 km easy (5:07–5:39/km). Focus on relaxed form and steady breathing. No watch-chasing today — just accumulate comfortable aerobic time.\"},\"wednesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. With 4 run days per week, spacing your hard efforts and long run with rest is what keeps the quality sessions actually high quality.\"},\"thursday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"10–11 km total: 2 km easy warm-up, 6 km at threshold pace (4:16/km), 2 km easy cool-down. Threshold work builds your lactate clearance capacity — directly relevant to holding marathon pace for 42 km.\"},\"friday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Let Thursday's tempo work absorb before your Saturday run.\"},\"saturday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"12–13 km easy (5:07–5:39/km). This is your mid-week aerobic top-up. Keep effort genuinely easy — the work is in the Sunday long run and Thursday tempo.\"},\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Priya. You're coming in with a strong recent base — 52–60 km weeks and a 1:32 half-marathon that puts your VDOT at 49.7, which is a genuinely solid platform for a 3:15 marathon goal. That target translates to 4:37/km race pace, which is well within reach given your current fitness. This first week mirrors what you've been doing: 60 km across 4 days, anchored by a Sunday long run and a Thursday tempo. The goal right now is consistency and aerobic development — no heroics needed. Your 4-days-per-week constraint is a feature, not a limitation; it gives your body real recovery between sessions. What does your energy feel like heading into this first week?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
